{
  "texts": [
    "Since the entire process needs processing 720 million tokens, we employed GPT-4o.",
    "Given that our natural experiment has a well-defined, treated group (Python and Rust) and a control group (i.e., R and Haskell) with one-shot policy adoption, we employ the classic Difference-in-Differences (DiD) framework (Meyer 1995) and estimate the Average Treatment Effect on Treated (ATT) using a two-way fixed effects (TWFE) model.",
    "We employ two complementary analytical approaches: first, we analyze matched pairs (Python vs. R and Rust vs. Haskell) to ensure comparability within similar programming domains; second, we combine all languages (Python+Rust vs. R+Haskell) to test overall robustness.",
    "One potential threat to causal estimation using DiD in a natural experiment setting is that the assignment of treatment could be non-random.",
    "In our context, while the assignment of treatment (i.e., language supported by GitHub Copilot) was a business decision and is therefore exogenous to the package themselves, the choice for the package to be on a programming language is likely endogenous."
  ]
}